  1. Collect a sample of geolocated tweets using your token. The geographic bounding box can span the entire globe or probably better for the exercise just focus on a given continent (e.g.Europe or Africa). Use the stream_tweets function from the rtweet package which we also discuss in the lab. If you e.g.use it in its form stream_tweets(q = c(yourgeocoordinates), timeout = veryhighnumberofseconds, parse = FALSE, file_name = "yourfilename.json"), you can let it run for some hours and it will continuously write the tweets into the JSON file name you specified. This way you can collect a sufficiently large sample, e.g.100,000 or 200,000, of geolocated tweets. Note that because of the parse = FALSE option, the function does not return parsed data as an object in R, but just writes it into a file. Should the code break, you can restart it e.g.with another file and eventually merge all files with tweets (when combining different files with tweets, be sure to delete duplicates based on e.g.the tweet ids as the Stream API can return the same tweets in different tries). To avoid this cell with the stream_tweets function to run again afterwards (e.g.when knitting the file), you can either use the cache option in the chunk, as shown below, to make sure it only re-runs after you change the code, or simply comment out the code after you have downloaded all tweets and saved the file. Please do not upload the large .json file with the tweets to GitHub! Rather store it somewhere on your computer. (10 points)

# Parse the tweets previously streamed into a json file into r. The result is a dataframe. Subsequently, we add the columns lat (latitude) and lng (longtitude) to the dataframe in order to be able to locate each tweets origin easier.

#Merging two json files into one
json1 <- parse_stream("geolocated_tweets.json")
json2 <- parse_stream("geolocated_tweets2.json")
geo_tweets_parsed <- rbind(json1, json2)
#write_json(jsonl, "geolocated_tweets5.json")

#geo_tweets_parsed <- parse_stream("geolocated_tweets8.json") # This parses a json file into R as a dataframe
#class(geo_tweets_parsed)
#names(geo_tweets_parsed)  # If you want to see which attributes of tweets and users you just streamed
geo_tweets_ltlng <- lat_lng(geo_tweets_parsed)

# Drop most variables of the dataframe and keep status_id, lat, lng, text, lang, country, country_code
geo_tweets_compressed <- geo_tweets_ltlng %>%
  select(status_id, lat, lng, text, lang, country, country_code)

# How many Tweets were collected?
print(paste(nrow(geo_tweets_compressed), "tweets have been collected."))
## [1] "162753 tweets have been collected."

  1. Now examine the language data. Which are the most popular languages? How many unique languages did you find? Can you determine which language code corresponds to tweets whose languages could not be predicted? (5 points)

Answer to Question 3 The most popular language is English In total, tweets in at least 50 languages were streamed. At least, as the language for a number of tweets could not be predicted. The language code und symbolizes undetermined and hence corresponds to tweets whose languages could not be predicted. The source for Twitters language codes is: https://www.loc.gov/standards/iso639-2/ISO-639-2_utf-8.txt

  1. Which countries produced the most and the least tweets? Then, create a data frame with only four variables: country, country_code, language, and n_tweets, i.e.the number of tweets for each combination of country and language. To make it smaller, you can keep only the rows for which n_tweets is greater than 0! Save this data frame into a file called part_a_country_language_distribution.csv we will work with it in part B. (3 points)

Answer to Question 5 People in the United Kingdom produced the most tweets, while people in Greenland and the Vatican produced the least tweets. This likely occurs due to market penetration of Twitter and population size of the countries.

# Creating a dataframe with three variables, `country_code`, `language`, and `n_tweets`, i.e. the number of tweets for each combination of country and language. As countries and languages only appear in the data frame if tweets with such values have been streamed, only rows where 'n_tweets' > 0 exist.
country_language_dist <- geo_tweets_compressed %>%
  select(country_code, lang) %>%
  group_by(country_code, lang) %>%
  summarise(n_tweets = n(), .groups = "drop") %>%
  drop_na()

#Add standardized country names to the country_codes as a new column
country_vector <- countrycode(country_language_dist$country_code, origin = "iso2c", destination = "country.name", custom_match = c('XK' = 'Kosovo'))
## Warning in countrycode(country_language_dist$country_code, origin = "iso2c", : Some values were not matched unambiguously:
country_language_dist$country <- country_vector

#Reordering and renaming columns
country_language_dist <- country_language_dist[,c("country", "country_code", "lang", "n_tweets")]
colnames(country_language_dist) <- c("country", "country_code", "language", "n_tweets")

# Which countries produced the least tweets?
country_language_dist %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarise(no_of_tweets = sum(n_tweets), .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(no_of_tweets)
## # A tibble: 56 x 2

country_language_dist %>%
  group_by(country) %>%
  summarise(no_of_tweets = sum(n_tweets), .groups = "drop") %>%
  arrange(desc(no_of_tweets))
